context: The etymological equivalent is in use in other languages, e.g., يَهُودِيّ yahūdī (sg.), al-yahūd (pl.), and بَنُو اِسرَائِيل banū isrāʼīl in Arabic, "<b4_0>Jude<b4_0/>" in German, "<b5_0>judeu<b5_0/>" in Portuguese, "<b6_0>juif<b6_0/>" in French, "jøde" in Danish and Norwegian, "judío" in Spanish, "jood" in Dutch, etc., but derivations of the word "<a3_0>Hebrew<a3_0/>" are also in use to describe a Jew, e.g., in Italian (<a1_0><b8_0>Ebreo<b8_0/><a1_0/>), in Persian ("Ebri/Ebrani" (Persian: عبری/عبرانی‎‎)) and Russian (<a2_0>Еврей, Yevrey<a2_0/>). The German word "<a0_0>Jude<a0_0/>" is pronounced [ˈjuːdə], the corresponding adjective "<b7_0>jüdisch<b7_0/>" [ˈjyːdɪʃ] (Jewish) is the origin of the word "Yiddish". (See Jewish ethnonyms for a full overview.)
